00:00:06.240 --> 00:00:15.120
So as I began to explore what I wanted to
do with my life I really became so focused

00:00:15.120 --> 00:00:22.310
on the different access to resources and opportunities
that different people have.

00:00:22.310 --> 00:00:28.060
And how that influences what happens generation
after generation after generation.

00:00:28.060 --> 00:00:34.330
So I was always fascinated by power, I was
always fascinated by, you know, what makes

00:00:34.330 --> 00:00:36.600
places the places that they are.

00:00:36.600 --> 00:00:38.239
Who decided that?

00:00:38.239 --> 00:00:41.110
And, where's the money going?

00:00:41.110 --> 00:00:46.019
And so, when I went to urban planning school,
I think I was somewhat of an outlier.

00:00:46.019 --> 00:00:51.739
There were a lot of people there who were
drawing maps and writing reports and doing

00:00:51.739 --> 00:00:57.670
all these technical functions, but not ever
stopping to think about fundamentally, where

00:00:57.670 --> 00:00:59.510
are our resources going?

00:00:59.510 --> 00:01:03.439
And how are those decisions being made?

00:01:03.439 --> 00:01:10.770
Ended up enrolling in a two year City and
Regional Planning Master's degree.

00:01:10.770 --> 00:01:16.399
And I thought, 'Great, this is where we'll
really get down to these issues that I've

00:01:16.399 --> 00:01:19.310
been living through my whole life.'

00:01:19.310 --> 00:01:26.890
And, when I got there nobody wanted to talk
about power.

00:01:26.890 --> 00:01:34.370
Nobody wanted to talk about how places became
they way they are, talk about money, talk

00:01:34.370 --> 00:01:38.569
about resources, talk about decision making.

00:01:38.569 --> 00:01:46.289
There were a handful of us and in my cohort
group of 30+ those of us who were asking those

00:01:46.289 --> 00:01:51.070
questions, we were all students of color.

00:01:51.070 --> 00:02:00.939
One was from Latin America, one was African
American, one was Filippino, there was myself

00:02:00.939 --> 00:02:03.600
and one was Chinese.

00:02:03.600 --> 00:02:06.819
And there we were, the five musketeers.

00:02:06.819 --> 00:02:17.390
And we had a group we called Student of Color
in Planning where we were trying to fill in

00:02:17.390 --> 00:02:24.410
the gaps of what we saw the actual underpinning
to everything we were learning was, but that

00:02:24.410 --> 00:02:26.750
no one was talking about.

