00:03:49.820 --> 00:03:52.250
or workshops with law enforcement officers.

00:03:52.250 --> 00:03:56.890
One of the things I do, usually in the first
five minutes, is to ask them.

00:03:56.890 --> 00:04:00.540
What's the very first thing you think when
you see a young Black or Latino male driving

00:04:00.540 --> 00:04:03.200
a nice car in your community?

00:04:03.200 --> 00:04:08.390
And almost invariably and with very few exceptions,
including among the officers of color, they

00:04:08.390 --> 00:04:10.710
will respond, 'probably a drug dealer.'

00:04:10.710 --> 00:04:12.930
I will then ask them, next question.

00:04:12.930 --> 00:04:17.010
When you see a young white male, same age,
driving the same kind of car in your community,

00:04:17.010 --> 00:04:18.160
what is the first thing you think?

00:04:18.160 --> 00:04:23.240
And, almost every time, without exception,
including among the officers of color.

00:04:23.240 --> 00:04:26.430
They will say, 'spoiled little rich kid, Daddy
probably bought him a car.'

00:04:26.430 --> 00:04:29.840
Now, on the one level, you know, we've been
together for five minutes, me and these cops

00:04:29.840 --> 00:04:33.610
and we've got a two hour--three hour workshop
coming and they're already outed themselves,

00:04:33.610 --> 00:04:37.729
fundamentally, as racist in the sense that
they've acknowledged their perception, which

00:04:37.729 --> 00:04:42.199
is solely based on skin color, is one that
is negative toward--in this case-- black or

00:04:42.199 --> 00:04:43.710
brown kids.

00:04:43.710 --> 00:04:44.830
How is that gonna manifest?

00:04:44.830 --> 00:04:49.639
Well, logic tells you, that if you're a police
officer who has that reaction, you may not

00:04:49.639 --> 00:04:54.099
like the spoiled rich kid--in fact you probably
don't--but you're not gonna hassle him because

00:04:54.099 --> 00:04:55.849
you're afraid his daddy might have some power.

00:04:55.849 --> 00:04:59.770
On the other hand, if you think the black
or brown kid is a dealer, you're gonna stop

00:04:59.770 --> 00:05:03.889
him, you're gonna search him, you're probably
not gonna find anything, according to the

00:05:03.889 --> 00:05:04.889
data.

00:05:04.889 --> 00:05:07.449
But now you're gonna have his name in the
system, you're gonna be on the lookout for

00:05:07.449 --> 00:05:11.180
his car, you're able to in effect, tag him
as a possible wrongdoer.

00:05:11.180 --> 00:05:14.729
And then that's how these folks get caught
up, young black and brown men, in particular,

00:05:14.729 --> 00:05:17.770
in the system being harassed over and over
and over again.

00:05:17.770 --> 00:05:21.680
While the white folks, according to the data,
are the ones more likely to have drugs in

00:05:21.680 --> 00:05:27.449
their car, more likely to bring drugs through
airports, the ones that are the least suspected

00:05:27.449 --> 00:05:30.360
are the ones that are actually the ones most
likely to be guilty.

00:05:30.360 --> 00:05:36.779
So you have the combination of personal bias
and the reality then of systemic mistreatment

00:05:36.779 --> 00:05:41.120
and then the irony of it all, is that it actually
leads you astray and doesn't allow you to

00:05:41.120 --> 00:05:42.120
do your job effectively.

00:05:42.120 --> 00:05:45.840
If you're a cop and thinks the black or brown
kid's got drugs and the white kid has drugs,

00:05:45.840 --> 00:05:47.169
you're not even doing your job well.

00:05:47.169 --> 00:05:52.199
So, at some level, you know, these personal
biases not only effect systemic behavior,

00:05:52.199 --> 00:05:57.250
but, they actually have profound larger social
consequences, in that, our criminal justice

00:05:57.250 --> 00:06:02.099
resources are really deployed in the completely
wrong areas.

